City of Chicago has the raw data from its police departmet available on its website. You can have access to the data from Jan 2001 to present (https://data.cityofchicago.org/Public-Safety/Crimes-2001-to-present/ijzp-q8t2/data).

I'm loading the data from 01/01/2001 to 07/27/2017 where nearly 6.4 million crimes has been recorded by Chicago Police.

In [3]:
df = pd.read_csv('C_-_2001_to_present.csv')

'Date' in csv date needs to be converted from 'string' to 'datetime' and will be saved to a pickle file for convenience for late use.

In [ ]:
column = df['Date']
column = pd.to_datetime(column, coerce=True)
df['Date'] = column

pickle.dump(column, open('c-2001-present_date.p', 'wb'))

calculating the number of years which we have data. (you cannot convert nanosecond to year directly, that's why we need to divide it by 365 days)

In [5]:
YEARS_OF_DATA = (max(df['Date'].values) - 
                 min(df['Date'].values))/np.timedelta64(365,'D')
In [406]:
print(str(YEARS_OF_DATA) + ' years of data')

16.5637271689 years of data

Sampling 1% is useful for tests, since doing all tests with over 6M events will be very slow.

In [6]:
# sampling 1% of data for tests
df_tmp = df.sample(frac=0.01)
df_sample = df_tmp.copy(deep=True)

This function will make most of the plots.

In [176]:
def plot_counter(counter, 
                 sample_frac=1,
                 last_year=False,
                 dot=False,
                 color='b',
                 label=None,
                 err=False,
                 yearly=False,
                 ax=None):
    '''plotting bars from counter
    
    counter:  counter object, a dictionary with the item as the key
        and the frequency as the value
    ax: an axis of matplotlib
    sample_frac: fraction of full sample
    last_year: if True predicts the last years' data
    dot: if False bar if True dot
    color: color of dots or bars
    err: if True, y-axis error bars will be plotted
    yearly: divides data by number of years
    returns: the axis wit the object in it
    '''
    if ax is None:
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
        ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    
    frequencies = np.array(np.divide(counter.values(),sample_frac))
    if yearly:
        frequencies = np.divide(frequencies, YEARS_OF_DATA)
    names = np.array(counter.keys())

    idx = np.argsort(names)
    frequencies = frequencies[idx]
    names = names[idx]
    
    x_coordinates = np.arange(len(frequencies))
    
    if dot:
        if last_year:
            frac = np.timedelta64(365, 'D')/\
                    (max(df_sample['Date']) -
                     pd.tslib.Timestamp('2017-01-01 00:00:00'))
            frequencies[-1] *= frac
        ax.plot(x_coordinates, frequencies,
                'o-',
                color=color,
                label=label)
    else:
        ax.bar(x_coordinates, frequencies,
               color=color,
               align='center')

        if last_year:
            names17 = ['2017']
            frac = np.timedelta64(365, 'D')/\
                    (max(df_sample['Date']) -
                     pd.tslib.Timestamp('2017-01-01 00:00:00'))
            frequencies17 = [frequencies[-1]*frac]
            ax.bar(x_coordinates[-1], frequencies17, 
                   align='center',
                   color=color,
                   alpha=0.3)

    if err:
        err = np.sqrt(frequencies)
        if last_year:
            err[-1] = err[-1] * frac
        ax.errorbar(x_coordinates, frequencies,
                    yerr=err,
                    ecolor=color,
                    fmt=None)
    
    ax.set_xlim(x_coordinates.min()-1,x_coordinates.max()+1)
    
    ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(plt.FixedLocator(x_coordinates))
    ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(plt.FixedFormatter(names))
    
    ax.get_yaxis().set_major_formatter(
        matplotlib.ticker.FuncFormatter(
            lambda x, p: format(int(x), ',')))
    
    labels = ax.get_xticklabels()
    plt.setp(labels, rotation=90)
    
    if yearly:
        ax.set_ylabel('Counts per year')
    else:
        ax.set_ylabel('Counts')
    
    return ax

Crime rate by year¶

def plot_share_segment(ax_, pType):
    filter = (df['Primary Type']==pType)
    ym = [i.strftime('%Y') for i in df['Date'][filter]]
    counts = Counter(ym)
    ax_ = plot_counter(counts,
                       sample_frac=1,
                       last_year=True,
                       dot=True,
                       err=True,
                       color='royalblue',
                       label='All ' + pType,
                       ax=ax_)

    filter = (df['Primary Type']==pType) &\
             (df['Arrest'])
    ym = [i.strftime('%Y') for i in df['Date'][filter]]
    counts = Counter(ym)
    ax_ = plot_counter(counts,
                       sample_frac=1,
                       last_year=True,
                       dot=True,
                       err=True,
                       color='red',
                       label=pType + ' with Arrest',
                       ax=ax_)
    
    ax_.legend(loc=0)
    
    return ax_

In [190]:
hChange = np.array([])
hChangeErr = np.array([])
aChange = np.array([])
aChangeErr = np.array([])

distrtic_list = np.unique(df['District'][df['Primary Type']=='HOMICIDE'])

frac = (max(df_sample['Date']) -
        pd.tslib.Timestamp('2017-01-01 00:00:00')) / np.timedelta64(365, 'D')

print('Change in homicide rate from (2005-2007) to\n' +
      '(2016-2017) in percent:')
print('\t\t\t\tAvg counts\tAvg counts\tChange in')
print('\t\t\t\tin 2005-2007\tin 2016-2017\tarrest')
print('Dist.\t% +/- uncertainty\tper year\tper year\t%')

for distrtic in distrtic_list:
    filter = (df['District']==distrtic) & (df['Primary Type']=='HOMICIDE')
    ym = [i.strftime('%Y') for i in df['Date'][filter]]
    counts = Counter(ym)
    
    base = counts['2005'] + counts['2006'] + counts['2007']
    avg_base = base / 3.0
    surge = counts['2016'] + counts['2017']
    avg_surge = surge / (1 + frac)
    percent_change = 100 * (avg_surge - avg_base)/avg_base
    err = percent_change * np.sqrt((1. / (surge + base)) +\
                                   (1. / (base)))
    hChange = np.append(hChange, percent_change)
    hChangeErr = np.append(hChangeErr, err)
    
    filter = (df['District']==distrtic) & (df['Primary Type']=='HOMICIDE') &\
             (df['Arrest'])
    ym = [i.strftime('%Y') for i in df['Date'][filter]]
    counts = Counter(ym)
    
    arr_base = counts['2005'] + counts['2006'] + counts['2007']
    arr_per_base = 1.0 * arr_base / base
    arr_surge = counts['2016'] + counts['2017']
    arr_per_surge = 1.0 * arr_surge / surge
    arr_change = arr_per_surge - arr_per_base
    arr_percent_change = 100 * arr_change
    err_a = abs(arr_percent_change) * np.sqrt((1. / (1 if arr_base==0 else arr_base)) +\
                          (1. / base) +\
                          (1. / (1 if arr_surge==0 else arr_surge)) +\
                          (1. / surge))
    aChange = np.append(aChange, arr_percent_change)
    aChangeErr = np.append(aChangeErr, err_a)

    print(str(int(distrtic)) + '\t' +\
          '{:0.1f}'.format(percent_change) + '\t' +\
          '{:0.1f}'.format(err) +'\t\t' +\
          '{:0.1f}'.format(avg_base) + '\t\t' +\
          '{:0.1f}'.format(avg_surge) + '\t\t' +\
          '{:0.1f}'.format(arr_percent_change))

def f(B,x):
    '''linear function y = m*x + b'''
    return B[0] * x + B[1]

linear = scipy.odr.Model(f)
myData = scipy.odr.RealData(hChange, aChange,
                            sx=hChangeErr,
                            sy=aChangeErr)

myodr = scipy.odr.ODR(myData, linear, beta0=[0., 0.])

myoutput = myodr.run()

myoutput.pprint()

 [ -1.61790144e-01   1.37274407e+01]]

Even though lower number crimes can be correlated to the lower number of arrest in Chicago (each can cause the other), but lower percentage and even number of arrests related to homicides during the increase of homicide rate (these correlations are relatively small and not conclusive) in the past few years can questionable. Note that data for arrests are only arrests at the the scene and the arrests made later are not in this data.
